<!DOCTYPE html>
<html>
<body>
<p>
Facts about <a knowl="defs/vec/sub">subspaces</a>.
</p>
<ul>
<li>
<i>Subspace criterion:</i> let \(W\subseteq V\) be nonempty.
If both
\(\alpha, \beta\in\mathbf F\) and \(u, v\in W\) implies
\[\alpha u + \beta v\in W,\]
then \(W\) is a subspace of \(V\).
<details>
<summary>
[explanation]
</summary>
<p>
Suppose both 
\(\alpha, \beta\in\mathbf F\) and \(u, v\in W\) implies
\(\alpha u + \beta v\in W\).
</p>
<p>
We now check the vector space axioms.
</p>
<ol>
<li>
Let \(a, b, c\in W\). Then since \(W\subseteq V\), we have \(a, b, c\in V\),
hence \(a + (b + c) = (a + b) + c\).
</li>
<li>
Let \(w\in W\). Then since \(1, -1\in\mathbf F\),
we have \[1w + (-1)w = w + (-1)w = w + (-w) = 0\in W.\]
Furthermore, since \(W\subseteq V\), \(w\in V\), hence
\(w + 0 = w = 0 + w\).
</li>
<li>
Let \(w\in W\). Then since \(0, -1\in\mathbf F\),
we have
\[0w + (-1)w = 0 + (-1)w = (-1)w = -w\in W.\]
Furthermore, since \(W\subseteq V\), \(w\in V\), hence
\[w + (-w) = 0 = (-w) + w.\]
</li>
<li>
Let \(a, b\in W\). Then since \(W\subseteq V\), we have \(a, b\in V\),
hence \(a + b = b + a\).
</li>
<li>
Let \(v\in W\). Then since \(W\subseteq V\), we have \(v\in V\),
hence \(1v = v\).
</li>
<li>
Let \(\alpha, \beta\in\mathbf F\), \(v\in W\). Then since \(W\subseteq V,\)
we have \(v\in V\), hence \(\alpha(\beta v) = (\alpha\beta)v\).
</li>
<li>
Let \(\alpha,\beta\in\mathbf F\), \(u, v\in W\). Then since \(W\subseteq V\),
we have \(u, v\in V\), hence
\[\alpha(u + v) = \alpha u + \alpha v\qquad\text{and}\qquad
(\alpha + \beta)v = \alpha v + \beta v.\]
</li>
</ol>
</details>
</li>
<li>
The trivial space \(\{0\}\) and \(V\) itself are both subspaces of \(V\).
<details>
<summary>
[explanation]
</summary>
<p>
Notice that \(\{0\}\) and \(V\) are both subsets of \(V\).
</p>
<p>
We checked that \(\{0\}\) is a
vector space <a knowl="facts/vec/trivial">here</a>,
and \(V\) is a vector space by assumption.
</p>
</details>
</li>
<li>
The (arbitrary) intersection of any nonempty set of subspaces of \(V\)
is another subspace of \(V\).
<details>
<summary>
[explanation]
</summary>
<p>
Let \(\{X_\iota\}_{\iota\in I}\) be a nonempty set of subspaces of \(V\).
Suppose \(\alpha, \beta\in\mathbf F\)
and \(u, v\in \bigcap_{\iota\in I} X_\iota\).
Then \(u, v\in X_\iota\) for all \(\iota\in I\), hence
\(\alpha u + \beta v\in X_\iota\) for all \(\iota\in I\),
hence \(\alpha u + \beta v\in \bigcap_{\iota\in I}X_\iota\).
</p>
</details>
</li>
</ul>
</body>
</html>
